{"title":"FuseMODNet: Real-Time Camera and LiDAR based Moving Object Detection for robust low-light Autonomous Driving","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Camera-only moving object detection (MOD) degrades under low illumination because image-based optical flow becomes unreliable; autonomous driving needs a robust, real-time MOD solution.","method":"FuseMODNet is a three-stream mid-fusion CNN that fuses RGB appearance, camera optical flow (rgbFlow from FlowNet), and LiDAR-derived dense optical flow (lidarFlow hallucinated from sparse LiDAR [35]) via separate encoders and feature-level concatenation, followed by an FCN8s decoder. The encoder uses an efficient ShuffleNet backbone (ShuffleSeg) for real-time operation. This fusion yields complementary motion cues that remain reliable in low light, improving moving-class IoU by 10.1% relatively on Dark-KITTI and 4.25% on KITTI over baselines, while running at 18 fps on 256×1224 images."},{"problem":"Public datasets for pixel-level moving/static segmentation are small and lack low-light imagery, limiting training and evaluation of MOD—especially for LiDAR–camera fusion.","method":"The authors automatically extend KittiMoSeg to 12,919 frames by projecting 3D LiDAR boxes to image space, computing object velocities from tracklets, estimating ego-motion from GPS, classifying objects as moving/static by velocity differencing, and refining masks with Mask R-CNN. To evaluate low-light robustness, they create Dark-KITTI by training UNIT on 2,000 KITTI day images and 2,000 BDD100K night images, generating 12,919 night counterparts aligned with the annotations."},{"problem":"It is unclear which fusion strategy (data-level vs feature-level vs hybrid) and motion representation (explicit optical flow vs implicit temporal learning) best balances accuracy and real-time constraints for MOD.","method":"They systematically compare early (data-level) fusion, mid (feature-level) fusion, and hybrid schemes across RGB, rgbFlow, lidarFlow, and LiDAR depth, and contrast explicit flow inputs with implicit motion learning from pairs of frames. Results show early fusion underperforms, while mid/hybrid fusion improves accuracy; explicit optical flow outperforms implicit motion learning. The best accuracy comes from three-stream mid-fusion RGB+rgbFlow+lidarFlow (e.g., Dark-KITTI moving IoU 43.5 vs 39.5 with RGB+rgbFlow; KITTI 51.46 vs 49.36), with documented real-time trade-offs (baseline 40 fps; two-stream 25 fps; three-stream 18 fps)."}]}
